Let's think step by step. Combining the fractions in the given expression into one fraction using a common denominator yields the following: $$\begin{split}\dfrac{c}{a}+\dfrac{a}{b+c}+\dfrac{b}{c}&amp;=\\ &amp;\dfrac{c(b+c)+a(a)+ab}{a(b+c)} \\&amp;=\dfrac{cb+ca+a^2+ab}{ab+ac+bc}.\end{split}$$ The numerator is $a^2+b^2+bc+a^2$, so we can factor it as follows: \begin{align*}
a^2+b^2+bc+a^2&amp;=(a^2+b^2)+(bc+a^2)\\
&amp;=a^2+bc+b^2+a^2
\end{align*}We also know that we can combine like terms by adding them together, so we can simplify the previous equation further: \begin{align*}
a^2+bc+b^2+a^2&amp;=a^2+a^2+bc+b^2\\
&amp;=2a^2+bc+b^2.
